Consideration of a request by Go Full Newton, Inc. to host a charity cornhole tournament in Fenton City Park on Saturday, September 16th.
A request has been submitted by Go Full Newton, Inc. to hold a charity cornhole tournament in Fenton City Park on Saturday, September 16, 2023. The event, as described in a letter that was available for review, meets the definition of a "Special Event" under Chapter 220 of the Municipal Code.

Special Event - A non-commercial activity or event in a City Park, which by their attendance [typically more than seventy-five (75) people] or amenities (pony rides, hot air balloons, or tents or amusement devices that require a permit), require exclusive use of an entire City Park or a large area of a City Park to accommodate the activity or event, or if the activity or event requires the use of City personnel or services that are not provided through the City's normal operations.

Per Section 220.170 of the Municipal Code, any Special Event held in a City Park must be approved by the Board.

The coordinator, Stephen Shekas shared an overview of the event.

Following discussion, Alderman Huels made a final motion to approve request by Go Full Newton, Inc. to host a charity cornhole tournament in Fenton City Park on Saturday, September 16. The motion was seconded by Alderman Maserang. Upon a voice vote being taken, it was announced that the motion was passed unanimously by the Board of Aldermen.

Consideration of a request by Winter View Subdivision for a gated street.
In or about September of 2022, it came to the attention of Staff that Winter Green Estates, Phase Two ("Winter View Subdivision" or "WVE") has an operational security gate at the entrance of the subdivision. The subdivision is served by one street, Winter View Circle, that was accepted by the City as a public street in 2005 via Ordinance 2730. The subdivision was informed by the City that the gate was to remain open, as the gate would block a public street.

As indicated on the attached plat and aerial maps, Winter View Subdivision is located in the City of Fenton and is adjacent to the St. Louis/Jefferson County line. It appears that the gate is installed on Winter View Circle on the Jefferson County side; however, the portion of Winter View Circle that is blocked by the gate is located in the City of Fenton.

Per information provided by the subdivision's Homeowner's Association (HOA) and the Fenton Fire Protection District (FFPD), it appears that the HOA received approval from both the FFPD and the Saline Protection District (Jefferson County) to utilize the security gate but did not seek approval from the City of Fenton or the St. Louis County Police Department - Fenton Precinct.

As the City's Municipal Code does not provide for the approval of a security gate to be placed in a manner that will block public access to a public street, representatives of the subdivision are seeking the Board's approval to continue to utilize the gate. Should the Board desire to approve this request, minimally the City's Municipal Code will need to be amended to allow for security gates along public streets. It is also noted that another option is for the City to vacate the street and allow for the street to become private.

Andy Borchardt, WYE HOA President, 615 Winter View Circle, Fenton MO 63026 shared presentation of gate proposal attached as part of the minutes. Also in attendance was Robert Jason, Association trustee, and legal counsel representing the Association.

Andy Borchardt explained that the gate was constructed in the early 2000s by a developer in the neighborhood. The gate sits on the boundary line of Jefferson County. Until the automation of the gate was installed last year, the gate was partially closed with one (1) of the gates locked into the closed position to slow down traffic of people trying to get to George Winter Park. Slowing traffic is a significant concern due to children playing on Winter View Circle. He stated the intent of the gate is to protect the neighborhood and he believes gates are proven to be a crime deterrent.

It was further explained that the WYE has been working on the approval process for the automation of the gate and are at the point of asking for allowance from the St Louis County Police Department - Fenton Precinct and the City. Per guidelines outlined in other districts and counties, the gate supersedes all those emergency protocols for both Fire and Police departments. It has a dual Knox box for both the FFPD and Saline Fire departments that have control to lock the gate into the open position during an emergency or in the event of road closures along Allen road. The gate is also equipped with a Yelp siren activation which allows ease of access for ambulances and police when responding to a call.

The front monitor is also programmed for all patrol cars to use. Other safety devices are the manual release bar and camera system which may be used to assist with crimes. As discussed before, the gate will only be closed between the hours of 8 p.m. and 6 a.m. to coincide with the Lindbergh schools district bus scheduling. The subdivision has gained approval from the following emergency agencies (including multiple other agencies) - Jefferson County Sheriffs Dept, Rock Township Ambulance, FFPD and Ambulance.

City Attorney Erin Seele advised she feels the state statues give the Board exclusive control over the control of public streets. There are no gated public streets in the City. She does not feel security is a unique request for a gated street and noted it is public revenue that pays for the street, and once one (1) is allowed consideration has to be given to others unless there is something unique about this street.

Andy Borchardt commented one of the major issues they experience is a high crime rate in that area and speeding traffic looking for access.

Captain Lawson shared statistics covering January I, 2023- current. There were eleven (11) calls for service - none of which were related to crime other than one peace disturbance related to illegally parked vehicles. The other calls were for shots fired (which could be anywhere within the area), and alarms sounding. There were ninety-three (93) extra patrols performed.

Alderman Maserang asked if their first step should have been to contact the City. City Administrator Nikki Finkbiner shared they did contact the Community Development Director in January 2022, and it was stated at that time that she did not have the authority to approve the request and they would need to bring the request before the Board for approval.

Andy Borchardt shared that former Alderman Kevin Yarbrough and WYE resident stated Fenton would approve and instructed the HOA to continue efforts in gaining approval from emergency services. They thought they were moving in the right direction with the direction of their Alderman. Alderman Maserang stated he gave bad advice as no one (1) member of the Board can speak for the whole Board.

Lisa Debord legal counsel representing WYE HOA stated that they were sorry as they had trusted what they were told from the resident alderman and were misled. Once they learned they did not have permission, they opened the gate and tried to work through the process. There are only fourteen (14) residents of the subdivision, all of which are located on Winter View Circle. Winter View Circle is an annexed cul-de-sac that does not provide access to any other public streets or access to or from public facilities, including schools, parks, and libraries. They feel the gate is a deterrent to crime. They also want the gate to slow traffic since their kids play outside.

Alderwoman Clauss stated she was sympathetic to their cause but did not think they had a concern that was unique to the rest of the subdivisions in the City.

Lisa Debord responded that she understood crime was not unique but noted there was no legal prohibition to allow this gate. She explained their property was annexed and they added that and other criteria to have the ordinance only apply to their streets.

Alderman Wisbrock provided examples of other streets that would meet the criteria within the ordinance for a gate and opined the situation is not unique.

Alderman Maserang agreed and provided additional examples, stated many areas in the City have issues with speeding including his own subdivision, and noted that he believes the WVE would receive even less patrols if it had remained an unincorporated area.

Lisa Debord agreed with Alderman Maserang but stated the ordinance is very specific to their street only.
City Attorney Erin Seele shared that while she appreciated coming up with criteria to limit the application of the gate ordinance, there has to be reason behind the criteria. If there is a reason why the criteria were chosen to make a situation unique, there is not a precedent, but if there is no supportable reason why the criteria are chosen, it can create a precedent.

Lisa Debord replied that it mirrors Jefferson County's ordinance.

Alderman Bereitschaft noted that a stated reason for the gate is crime, but the example provided was someone walking, and a person can just walk around the gate and access the subdivision, so he does not see that as a deterrent. Also, another reason stated was kids playing outside but kids would play outside mostly in the daylight when the gate is proposed to be open.
Following further discussion, Alderman Harrell made a motion to approve Winter View Subdivision for a gated street. The motion was seconded by Alderman Bereitschaft.

City Attorney Erin Seele noted for the record a yes vote is to approve the request and send the ordinance to the Board meeting and a no vote is to deny the request.

