Discussion regarding placing Proposition M on the April 2024 election ballot.
The Missouri Constitution allows municipalities to impose an additional sales tax of up to three percent (3%) on retail sales of adult-use marijuana with voter approval, "Proposition M". Last year, the Board opted not to place Proposition M on the April 2023 General Election ballot - as the desire was to have the citizens of Fenton vote on Proposition U (use tax on out-of-state purchase).

If the Board desires to place Proposition M on the April 2024 election ballot, the City would need to file an Ordinance with the Board of Elections in late December. Based on this, Staff is seeking direction from the Board in the next few months.

Staff does not have any financial projections related to this sales tax as only one (1) dispensary is currently located within the City limits; however, funds generated from the tax would not be restricted. It cannot be a layered tax, noting that St. Louis County does not impose their approved Proposition M tax in the City limits of Fenton.

NOTE: Approval of Proposition M would only impose an additional three percent (3%) sales tax on adult use (recreational) marijuana and does not apply to medical marijuana. Additionally, the three percent (3%) sales tax on adult use marijuana would be in addition to the six percent (6%) state tax on recreational marijuana and all other applicable sales tax in place.

Discussion ensued regarding how many municipalities passed the tax so far.

Alderman Wisbrock expressed he is in favor of placing it on the ballot.

Following discussion, Alderman Bereitschaft made a motion to forward to the September Board of Aldermen meeting a bill placing Proposition M on the April 2024 election ballot. The motion was seconded by Alderman Cruts. Upon a voice vote being taken, it was announced that the motion was passed unanimously by the Board of Aldermen.

